Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Wilfred Kotey¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area by Ford Motors. The dataset to be explored today was obtained in the month of February in 2019.

Data Cleaning¶

The dataset needs to be cleaned a bit for the exploration to be done

  1. Datatype of start_time and end_time should be changed from object to datetime format
  2. bike_id, start_station_id, and end_station_id should be changed to integers
  3. An age column should be added by subtracting the year of birth of members from the year the information was gathered
  4. user_type, member_gender, and bike_share_for_all_trip should be changed to category format
  5. New columns should be created for weekdays, start and end time hours and duration of trips in minutes

In [83]:
# Create a column for the start time weekday
rides['weekday_of_start'] = rides['start_time'].dt.strftime('%A')
In [84]:
# Create a column for the start and end time hour
rides['start_hour'] = rides['start_time'].dt.hour
rides['end_hour'] = rides['end_time'].dt.hour
In [85]:
# Create a final column for duration in minutes
rides['duration_min'] = rides['duration_sec']/60
rides['duration_min'] = rides['duration_min'].astype(int)

The codes for the changing and adding of the new columns as stated above was obtained from https://docs.python.org/3/library/datetime.html#strftime-and-strptime-behavior

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 174952 rows and 21 columns for the Ford GoBike System in a bike-sharing system. The columns include; duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, age, weekday_of_start, start_hour, end_hour and duration_min

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The data gives information about the usage of the bike service based on people's age, gender and whether or not they use the service frequently and also which gender takes longer trips. It can also be used to determine what day of the week or particular hour of the day when the service is in high demand.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The age, gender and user types of the customers and also the start and end times of the bike trips

def barplot(value, title, xlabel, ylabel, plt_order=None, base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(x = value, color=base_color , data = rides, order=plt_order)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])
day_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
barplot('weekday_of_start', 'Distribution of count of bike rides on each day', 'Weekdays', 'Number of Bike Trips', plt_order=day_order)

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution for the duration of the trips in seconds was extremely skewed to the right showing that most people finished their rides earlier and that as time went on, less and less people continued the trip.

    sb.boxplot(x = value1, y = value2, color=base_color , data = rides)
    plt.ylim(-10, 80)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()
    
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])

From the boxplot it can be observed that the females and other gender took longer trips as compared to the males

def barplot(value1, value2, plot_order, title, xlabel, ylabel):

    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

The bike service is a good way to move through the city. There are two users, subscribers and casual users. The subscribers use the service daily probably to and from work considering the hours when the service is most in use during the day, that is, around 8-9am in the morning and 5-6pm in the evening and casual users usually take trips on weekends around the city. Females have also been observed to take longer trips than males probably because they are much younger on the average.
